{"parse":{"title":"Jerk (play)","pageid":26897651,"revid":786258756,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vevent\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" class=\"summary\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;font-style: italic\">Jerk</th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space: nowrap\">Written by</th><td class=\"description\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/Dennis_Cooper\" title=\"Dennis Cooper\">Dennis Cooper</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space: nowrap\">Characters</th><td>\nDavid Brooks, <a href=\"/wiki/Dean_Corll\" title=\"Dean Corll\">Dean Corll</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Elmer_Wayne_Henley\" title=\"Elmer Wayne Henley\">Elmer Wayne Henley</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space: nowrap\">Date premiered</th><td>\n5&#160;March&#160;2008<span style=\"display:none\">&#160;(<span class=\"bday dtstart published updated\">2008-03-05</span>)</span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space: nowrap\">Original language</th><td>\nFrench</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space: nowrap\">Genre</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Puppetry\" title=\"Puppetry\">Puppet play</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><i><b>Jerk</b></i> is a one-person <a href=\"/wiki/Puppetry\" title=\"Puppetry\">puppet play</a> by the American writer <a href=\"/wiki/Dennis_Cooper\" title=\"Dennis Cooper\">Dennis Cooper</a>, made in collaboration with director Gis\u00e8le Vienne and performer Jonathan Capdevielle, based on Cooper's 1993 novel of the same name.<sup id=\"cite_ref-prog_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-prog-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> It is based on the story of <a href=\"/wiki/Serial_killer\" title=\"Serial killer\">serial killer</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Dean_Corll\" title=\"Dean Corll\">Dean Corll</a> and his teenage accomplices David Brooks and <a href=\"/wiki/Elmer_Wayne_Henley\" title=\"Elmer Wayne Henley\">Elmer Wayne Henley</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-prog_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-prog-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The play develops the conceit that Brooks has learnt puppetry in prison and, as part of his rehabilitation, acts out the murders in which he participated via the use of glove puppets and <a href=\"/wiki/Ventriloquism\" title=\"Ventriloquism\">ventriloquism</a>. The performance also involved sections in which the audience read about the murders in pamphlets, entitled \"Two Texts for a Puppet Play by David Brooks\" that were distributed.\n</p><p>The production premiered on 5 March 2008 in <a href=\"/wiki/Brest,_France\" title=\"Brest, France\">Brest, France</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The play was also performed in an English-language version at the <a href=\"/wiki/South_London_Gallery\" title=\"South London Gallery\">South London Gallery</a> as part of the <i>Paris Calling</i> season of performing arts, opening on 1 July 2009.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Its performance included music by <a href=\"/wiki/Peter_Rehberg\" title=\"Peter Rehberg\">Peter Rehberg</a>.\n</p><p>In his analysis of <i>Jerk</i>, theater scholar Jordan Schildcrout states, \"The production becomes a meta-puppet show when the actor playing David is giving voice to the puppets playing the killers, who in turn give voice to the puppets playing the corpses... In the final scenario, though, David abandons his puppets and does all the voices, including his own, as a ventriloquist, not moving his lips, as if he is also losing his humanity, becoming increasingly inanimate. In the story, David is ultimately alone in a house of corpses, and in performance he is alone on an empty stage, with only lifeless puppets sharing the space.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Jerk_(play)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-prog-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-prog_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-prog_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">From the programme <i>Paris Calling: A Franco-British Season of Performing Arts 09</i>; see also <i>Jerk</i> on denniscooper.net and the <i>Jerk</i> page on Gis\u00e8le Vienne's website.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">See the <i>Jerk</i> page on Gis\u00e8le Vienne's website.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">See the SLG Events webpage.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Schildcrout, Jordan (2014). <i>Murder Most Queer: The Homicidal Homosexual in the American Theater</i>. University of Michigan Press. pp.&#160;171\u2013172. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780472072323\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780472072323\">9780472072323</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Murder+Most+Queer%3A+The+Homicidal+Homosexual+in+the+American+Theater&amp;rft.pages=171-172&amp;rft.pub=University+of+Michigan+Press&amp;rft.date=2014&amp;rft.isbn=9780472072323&amp;rft.aulast=Schildcrout&amp;rft.aufirst=Jordan&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJerk+%28play%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Sources\">Sources</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Jerk_(play)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Sources\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Dennis_Cooper\" title=\"Dennis Cooper\">Cooper, Dennis</a>. 1993. <i>Jerk</i>. San Francisco: Artspace. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-9631095-1-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-9631095-1-0\">0-9631095-1-0</a>.</li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.denniscooper.net/jerkplay.htm\"><i>Jerk</i> on denniscooper.net</a>. Retrieved 7 April 2010.</li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.g-v.fr/creations/ve-jerk-frameset.htm\"><i>Jerk</i> on Gis\u00e8le Vienne</a>. Retrieved 7 April 2010.</li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.southlondongallery.org/docs/live/event.jsp?id=64&amp;sid=40&amp;view=past\">SLG Events</a>. Retrieved 7 April 2010.</li>\n<li>Viegener, Matias. 1993. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-14156152.html\">Review of the novel <i>Jerk</i></a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Artforum\" title=\"Artforum\">Artforum</a></i> 22 June. Retrieved 7 April 2010.</li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2223\nCached time: 20180917193638\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.116 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.162 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 698/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node co